  "prompt": "What is the difference between Visual Basic and Visual Studio and what are the languages supported by .net framework?",
  "response": "### Differences between Visual Basic and Visual Studio:\n\n1. **Visual Basic (VB):**\n   - **Definition:** Visual Basic is a programming language developed by Microsoft. It is an event-driven language that is easy to learn and use, making it a popular choice for developing Windows applications.\n   - **Purpose:** It is used for creating desktop applications, web applications, and even mobile applications through various frameworks.\n   - **Syntax:** VB has a syntax that is closer to natural language, making it easier for beginners to understand and write code.\n\n2. **Visual Studio:**\n   - **Definition:** Visual Studio is an Integrated Development Environment (IDE) developed by Microsoft. It provides a comprehensive set of tools for software development, including code editing, debugging, and testing.\n   - **Purpose:** Visual Studio supports multiple programming languages and frameworks, allowing developers to build a wide range of applications, from simple console programs to complex enterprise-level software.\n   - **Features:** It includes features like IntelliSense (code completion), debugging tools, a rich editor, and support for various project types (console, web, desktop, mobile, etc.).\n\n### Languages Supported by the .NET Framework:\n\nThe .NET Framework supports multiple programming languages, allowing developers to choose the one that best fits their needs. Some of the primary languages supported include:\n\n1. **C# (C Sharp):**\n   - A modern, object-oriented programming language developed by Microsoft. It is widely used for building Windows applications, web applications, and games (via Unity).\n\n2. **Visual Basic .NET (VB.NET):**\n   - An evolution",
